g.text: The audio spectrum of a beehive provides valuable
insights into the colony’s health and activity. Bees
produce different sounds depending on their
behavior, such as the low-frequency hum of a calm
hive or the higher-pitched buzzing of an agitated
colony. By analyzing the frequency spectrum using
Short-Time Fourier Transform (STFT), we can detect
patterns related to swarming, queenlessness, or
stress. Changes in sound intensity and frequency
changes, or even early signs of disease. Monitoring
the audio spectrum helps beekeepers gain a deeper
understanding of hive dynamics without opening the
hive, reducing stress on the bees.
